<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1924-11-22T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1924-11-22T00:00:00-05:00" n="365" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d365">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/5786: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Shanghai</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Cunningham</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Shanghai</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1924-11-22"><hi rend="italic">November 22,
                                    1924</hi></date>.<lb/>[Received November 22—1:45
                                p.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>Following from Nanking: <quote rend="blockquote">
                                <p>“November 22, 11 a.m. Please send following telegram to the
                                    Department: ‘Marshal Chi embarrassed by Wu’s unauthorized use of
                                    his name in manifesto proclaiming Yangtze military government,
                                    and has repeated circular telegram endorsing Tuan. He will
                                    assist Wu defensively but considers aggression
                                    impracticable.</p>
                                <p>Situation delicate and uncertain. Davis.’ ”</p></quote></p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Cunningham</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>